clear the zone Leafs kill the Giordano penalty Rielly shot off the rush goes wide Liljegren shot tipped wide McDonagh clears the puck out of harm’s way Kerfoot penalized for holding Hagel on the backcheck, and Lightning go back on the power play (0:44 left) Hedman can’t keep the puck in the zone Kucherov with quick pass into the slot to Point, but Campbell makes the save LIGHTNING GOAL: Hedman cleans up a loose puck at the right post. Lightning 1, Maple Leafs 0. (0.25 left) (Lightning lead 1-0 after one period) Pregame scouting report What. Was. That? Yes, we knew Lightning-Maple Leafs had the makings of a competitive series after the teams split their four regular-season games and finished five points apart in the Atlantic Division standings. We expected goals (Toronto scored five), star power (league goal-scoring leader Auston Matthews had two of them) and physical play (113 combined penalty minutes), and we got every bit of that. What we didn’t expect was for the two-time defending Stanley Cup champions to pull a disappearing act, as they did in a 5-0 loss in Game 1 Monday in Toronto. The Lightning hadn’t lost a playoff game by five goals since the franchise’s first postseason in 1996. And they hadn’t been held scoreless in a playoff game since the 2018 Eastern Conference final, a span of 33 games. A power play that had been incendiary entering the game went 0-for-5 and yielded a shorthanded goal. Reigning Conn Smythe Trophy winner Andrei Vasilevskiy allowed five goals on 33 shots. His counterpart, Jack Campbell, pitched a shutout in only his eighth career postseason start. After 60 minutes of play, the biggest number on the Lightning scoresheet was 17, the number of penalty minutes for defenseman Jan Rutta. The next biggest? Forward Corey Perry’s 16 PIM. Tampa Bay’s three most potent scoring threats, Steven Stamkos, Nikita Kucherov and Brayden Point, had a combined six shots on goal, despite 12:51 of Lightning power-play time. (Deep breath) Okay, now the good news. No team has been better at bouncing back from a loss over the past two postseasons than the Lightning, which won the game following each of their 14 losses during that span. They came back to win all three series in which they had dropped Game 1, including the 2020 Cup final against the Stars. Of course, just because they have done so in the past doesn’t necessarily mean they will do it again. They will have to get bodies in front of Campbell, fix their entries on the power play, keep better track of Matthews and find a way to match the Maple Leafs’ tempo. But history shows us it is well within their capabilities, which means there won’t be any panic in the locker room. The Lightning still have the more talented roster top to bottom, the better defense, the experience of the past two postseasons and, Game 1 notwithstanding, the best goaltender in the world. Meanwhile, the Maple Leafs will be without veteran forward Kyle Clifford, one of just two Toronto players with Stanley Cup rings (Jake Muzzin is the other). Clifford was suspended for one game for boarding Ross Colton. Michael Bunting is back in the Leafs’ lineup and will skate with Matthews and Mitch Marner on the top line. Can the Lightning put Monday’s performance behind them and get back to the game that carried them to wins in seven of their final nine regular-season contests, including an 8-1 thrashing of the Maple Leafs on April 21? We’ll find out together, starting at 7:30 p.m., as the Lightning aim to even the series before it heads to Tampa. Gameday scene • • • The Tampa Bay Times has commemorated the Lightning’s second consecutive Stanley Cup title with a new hardcover coffee table book, Striking Twice. Order now. Sign up for Lightning Strikes, a weekly newsletter from Bolts beat writer Eduardo A. Encina that brings you closer to the ice. Never miss out on the latest with the Bucs, Rays, Lightning, Florida college sports and more. Follow our Tampa Bay Times sports team on Twitter and Facebook.